export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>High-entropy alloys (HEAs) — more precisely the family of multi-principal-element alloys (MPEAs) and compositionally disordered systems — are this report's benchmark class. The convergence is too exact to ignore: the hardest documented case in the MS25 validation suite (Maxson et al., JCIM 2025) is a five-element alloy, and the same class sits first on two governments' materials agendas.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"186\">[186]</sup> These alloys' useful properties emerge from chemical disorder, and disorder is precisely what the current simulation stack cannot price. I hold no brief for the founding entropy-stabilization premise — it failed quantitative testing, and §6.4 gives the numbers — which is why the surviving records matter: earned against a skeptical baseline, they define the demand for fixing the prediction problem below.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s6-1-1", "html": "<p>The policy demand is verbatim, not inferred. China's 15FYP Outline orders breakthroughs in &quot;高端特殊钢、高品质高温合金&quot; (high-end special steels, high-quality superalloys), and industry planning documents call aero-engine single-crystal superalloy blades a chokepoint &quot;still subject to foreign control,&quot; with a 1,200 °C Ni single-crystal target (+20% stress-rupture, +30% hot-corrosion resistance).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"22\">[22]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"186\">[186]</sup> ARPA-E's ULTIMATE program targets continuous operation above 1,300 °C (T4 above 1,800 °C with coatings) for 5–7% gas-turbine efficiency gains and 10–20 Quads by 2050, because single-crystal Ni superalloys &quot;have reached the limit&quot; below 1,100 °C.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"50\">[50]</sup> Substitution pressure compounds it: Co and Ni sit on DOE's 2023 Critical Materials List, and Cr, Co, Ni, Re, Hf, Ta, W, Nb, V, and Zr are all on the USGS lists — the elements HEA design freedom must engineer around.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"187\">[187]</sup></p>\n<p>The value anchors are measured, not projected. CrMnFeCoNi exceeds 1 GPa tensile strength with fracture toughness above 200 MPa·m<span class=\"math\">$^{1/2}$</span> — properties that <em>improve</em> at cryogenic temperatures<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"51\">[51]</sup> — and the CrCoNi family holds toughness records down to 20 K.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"188\">[188]</sup> VNbMoTaW retains 842–862 MPa yield strength at 600–1,000 °C, significantly outperforming Inconel 718.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"189\">[189]</sup> These records are expensive to find because their mechanisms live in disorder physics — stacking-fault-energy (SFE) distributions, short-range order (SRO), local chemical environments — the same quantities §6.2 shows the stack mis-computes by factors, not percents.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s6-2-1", "html": "<p>Against MS25's usability thresholds (2.5 meV/atom energy, 35 meV/Å force), all five tested architectures — MACE, NequIP, Allegro, MTP, Torch-ANI — post energy errors &quot;4–5× larger&quot; than threshold on the five-element EAM-HEA dataset, roughly 10–12.5 meV/atom; forces stay within 35 meV/Å except MTP at 189 meV/Å.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> Worse, MTP's learning is non-monotonic: a 100-point model posts a force MAE of 117 meV/Å, just 61% of the 1,000-point model's error — ten times the data made forces ~1.6× <em>worse</em>, a pathology attributed to high elemental composition space.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> The damning comparison: fixed-composition systems in the same suite reach ~0.2 meV/atom with 1,000 training images, so the composition tax at equal data budget is 50–60×.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> And low energy/force errors do not certify observables: HEA lattice-constant errors in MS25's derived-observable tests do not correlate with energy/force errors.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s6-2-2", "html": "<p>One benchmark suite finds GRACE-2L-OMAT, a foundation potential, 617.9 meV/atom and 193.5 meV/Å off the 25-element HEA25S dataset zero-shot — roughly 250× and 5.5× the thresholds — with fine-tuning recovering 3.5 meV/atom and 85 meV/Å.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup> Part is functional mismatch (PBE training versus PBEsol labels); the rest is coverage — the 176× zero-shot-to-fine-tuned spread is the sharpest single quantification that universal MLIPs fail in many-element space.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup> The specialized route plateaus instead: HEA25S-4-NN, compressing 25 d-block elements into four pseudo-elements, holds ~10 meV/atom on bulk, 13–16 meV/atom on surfaces, and 25.7 meV/atom on a targeted segregation set; its authors claim only &quot;semi-quantitative accuracy,&quot; with ad-hoc retraining plus spin-polarized DFT labels &quot;still needed to achieve errors of a few meV/atom.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"190\">[190]</sup> Its learning curve flattens (150 → 30 meV/atom from 200 to 1,000 structures); forces degrade with diversity — one general-purpose-potential study reports force RMSE growing 76 → 196 → 269 meV/Å from 3- to 4- to 13-component tests.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"190\">[190]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"191\">[191]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s6-2-3", "html": "<p>SRO is not a perturbation; it is the ground state. Atomistic simulations show prevalent local chemical order arising at the solidification front even under a 10<span class=\"math\">$^{11}$</span> K/s cooling rate — so the random solid solution that special-quasirandom-structure (SQS) models approximate is the wrong reference state for FCC MPEAs.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"192\">[192]</sup> Converging SRO takes hybrid Monte Carlo/molecular dynamics on 500-atom cells over ~4 ns — infeasible for direct DFT, forcing MLIP-mediated sampling that inherits the errors above.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"193\">[193]</sup> SFE, the Cantor-class design input, is a distribution, not a scalar: DFT on NiCoCr finds local-environment fluctuations spanning −200 to +60 mJ/m².<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"194\">[194]</sup> And even the best free-energy machinery cannot close a property-level gap: a hierarchical EAM→MTP→FEP→DFT ladder for TaVCrW melting, internally consistent to &lt;0.5 meV/atom, still carries ±50 K numerical uncertainty (a 1 meV/atom free-energy error shifts <span class=\"math\">$T_m$</span> ~10 K) and lands 160–193 K below CALPHAD (2,376 K PBE, 2,409 K LDA versus 2,569 K) — with no experimental melting data to arbitrate; the CALPHAD entry rests on sub-binary data only, and SRO shifts <span class=\"math\">$T_m$</span> a further ~20 K.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"195\">[195]</sup></p>\n<p><strong>Table 6.1 — The composition-space error ledger (thresholds: 2.5 meV/atom energy, 35 meV/Å force; figures as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Test case</th>\n<th>Energy error</th>\n<th>Force error</th>\n<th>Verdict vs threshold</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>MS25 FeNiCrCoCu EAM-HEA; five architectures (MACE, NequIP, Allegro, MTP, Torch-ANI)</td>\n<td>4–5× threshold (≈10–12.5 meV/atom) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup></td>\n<td>≤35 meV/Å except MTP 189 meV/Å <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup></td>\n<td>Fail energy; MTP fails force; MTP non-monotonic in data</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>GRACE-2L-OMAT zero-shot on HEA25S (one benchmark suite)</td>\n<td>617.9 meV/atom <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup></td>\n<td>193.5 meV/Å <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup></td>\n<td>~250× / ~5.5× — zero-shot collapse</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>GRACE-2L-OMAT fine-tuned on HEA25S</td>\n<td>3.5 meV/atom <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup></td>\n<td>85 meV/Å <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup></td>\n<td>1.4× / 2.4× — near-threshold, generality surrendered</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>HEA25S-4-NN (25 d-block elements → 4 pseudo-elements)</td>\n<td>~10 bulk; 13–16 surfaces; 25.7 meV/atom targeted <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"190\">[190]</sup></td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>4–10×; authors: &quot;semi-quantitative&quot;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>NiCoCr SFE vs local environment (DFT)</td>\n<td>distribution −200 to +60 mJ/m² <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"194\">[194]</sup></td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>single scalar SFE undefined</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>TaVCrW melting (EAM→MTP→FEP→DFT ladder)</td>\n<td>DFT 2,376/2,409 K vs CALPHAD 2,569 K <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"195\">[195]</sup></td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>160–193 K unresolved; no experiment to arbitrate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>UNEP-v1 vs classical EAM, multicomponent formation energies (one study)</td>\n<td>MLIP 75/60 vs EAM 695/1,122 meV/atom <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"191\">[191]</sup></td>\n<td>76/196/269 meV/Å (3/4/13 components) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"191\">[191]</sup></td>\n<td>classical fallback closed; forces grow with diversity</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Three patterns emerge. First, failures scale with elemental diversity, not model size: architectures posting ~0.2 meV/atom at fixed composition sit at 10–12.5 meV/atom here, and UNEP-v1's force error more than triples from three to thirteen components. Second, both best results are admission-priced: GRACE reaches 3.5 meV/atom only after fine-tuning on the target distribution — generality surrendered — and HEA25S-4-NN reaches ~10 meV/atom only by compressing 25 elements into four pseudo-elements — chemical resolution surrendered. Third, when ground truth is itself a distribution (SFE) or an unresolved 160–193 K disagreement (<span class=\"math\">$T_m$</span>), &quot;train a better potential&quot; is an incomplete strategy; reference data need SRO-resolved observables and magnetic labels. The bright line is directional: zero-shot to fine-tuned is a 176× reduction on one dataset — the dominant failure is coverage, which is purchasable, not capacity.</p>\n<div class=\"pullbox\">\n<p><strong>Case box 6.1 — MS25-HEA: the cleanest isolation of the composition-space problem.</strong> The construction is the argument. MS25's HEA ground truth is generated not by DFT but by a classical embedded-atom-method (EAM) potential — pairwise plus density terms, a 5.804 Å cutoff, no quantum mechanics anywhere.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> EAM potentials are &quot;very easily learned by MLIPs with just one or two elements, such that they are used as training examples in documentation.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> The dataset then changes one variable: five transition metals (Fe, Ni, Cr, Co, Cu) mix freely, each ≥10%, across 600–1,200 K and 1 atm.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> Every tested architecture fails energy thresholds by 4–5×; MTP's forces degrade with added data.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> Because the ground truth is a simple analytic function, the usual excuses are eliminated — no DFT label noise, no functional error, no missing long-range physics (the EAM is strictly short-ranged), no rare-event sampling. The only variable is element count. What breaks is therefore the MLIP's ability to represent diverse local chemical environments, not its ability to fit a potential-energy surface. I treat MS25-HEA as the field's controlled experiment on composition space: it converts &quot;MLIPs struggle with HEAs&quot; from anecdote into mechanism, and it defines the acceptance test any disorder-native architecture must pass.</p>\n</div>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s6-3-1", "html": "<p>Equivariant architectures deliver 1.5–2× lower energy and force errors on disordered systems in MS25 — real, but insufficient at 1,000 training images, and the Six Open Questions perspective notes the gain is often negated once parameter count is controlled for.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"108\">[108]</sup> The cheaper lever is Δ-learning on classical priors, MS25's own recommendation: let EAM supply the majority of interactions and train the MLIP only on deviations — though UNEP-v1's formation-energy comparison (EAM ~10× worse than MLIPs) shows the prior must be corrected, never trusted.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"191\">[191]</sup> The highest-ceiling lever is element-wise Mixture-of-Experts routing (arXiv:2603.07977): it beats configuration-level routing, achieves state of the art on OMat24/OC20M/OMol25, and learns periodic-table-aligned expert specialization — an architecture answering MS25's diagnosis directly, not yet validated on any HEA benchmark.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"196\">[196]</sup> Scoreboard Rows 1 and 2 bind here: the GRACE fine-tuning collapse (617.9 → 3.5 meV/atom) is Row 2's micro-dose logic at composition scale, and Row 1's non-equilibrium data composition is the dataset lever not yet tried on this class.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup> &quot;Solved&quot; has a concrete shape: ≤2.5 meV/atom on a DFT-labeled, multi-composition benchmark with SRO-resolved observables and magnetic labels where Cr or Mn are present; the current bests are 3.5 meV/atom on one fine-tuned dataset and ~10 meV/atom for the one model spanning 25 elements.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"190\">[190]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s6-4-1", "html": "<p>The founding hypothesis did not survive contact with thermodynamics. Senkov, Miller, Miracle, and Woodward screened over 130,000 alloy systems and found that &quot;solid solution alloys become <em>less</em> likely as the number of alloy elements increases&quot; — configurational entropy rises slowly while the probability of at least one element pair favoring intermetallics rises faster.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"197\">[197]</sup> Schön and co-workers, using cluster-variation thermodynamics fitted to DFT, found configurational entropy's effect &quot;small, even marginal,&quot; with frustration between conflicting interactions doing the actual stabilizing.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"198\">[198]</sup> The field's own vocabulary migration — from &quot;entropy-stabilized single phase&quot; to &quot;complex concentrated alloys&quot; with deliberately multi-phase microstructures — is the implicit concession.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"199\">[199]</sup> On the application side, refractory HEAs remain room-temperature-brittle and oxidation-prone: &quot;after decades of efforts to overcome these severe drawbacks, refractory alloys are still unable to replace nickel-based superalloys,&quot; and add density and cost against single-crystal Ni running with thermal-barrier coatings.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"200\">[200]</sup></p>\n<p>And yet the records of §6.1 survive every one of these critiques, because their mechanisms are understood: the cryogenic toughness traces to the SFE-distribution-driven nanotwinning transition — the same quantity §6.2.3 shows the stack renders as a scalar.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"51\">[51]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"194\">[194]</sup> My verdict: entropy was the wrong theory of a real phenomenon. A minority of disordered alloys are genuinely superior; the ab initio plus MLIP stack cannot yet find and certify them faster than arc-melt-and-characterize iteration. Prediction quality, not enthusiasm, is the binding constraint on the class's maturation.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s6-5-1", "html": "<p>China's 15FYP breakthrough tier names the class verbatim, and Guangzhou's 15FYP frontier-materials box lists 高熵合金 (high-entropy alloys) explicitly among core-technology targets; the single-crystal superalloy blade is flagged as a chokepoint still subject to foreign control.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"22\">[22]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"32\">[32]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"186\">[186]</sup> Washington has put phased money behind the same gap: ULTIMATE committed <span class=\"math\">$28M announced 2020, then $</span>20M across 17 Phase 1 and $23M across 10 Phase 2 projects, refractory complex-concentrated-alloy teams among performers; a DARPA/AFRL-commissioned TMS accelerator study acknowledges promise and tooling gap in one document; and the critical-minerals lists put Co/Cr/Re substitution on statutory footing, with hypersonics/defense demand running through AFRL's refractory-HEA lineage and ONR-funded MPEA simulation.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"50\">[50]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"201\">[201]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"187\">[187]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"202\">[202]</sup> I read both systems as paying for the same missing capability — composition-space prediction — from opposite supply-chain anxieties. Neither owns the solution, because it does not yet exist at threshold accuracy.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s6-6-1", "html": "<p>This chapter feeds the roadmap's fourth chain: disorder-native MLIPs (MoE-routed, SRO-aware) → HEAs and superalloys with targeted properties → &gt;1,300 °C turbines and cryogenic-tough structures → efficient aviation, space, LNG, and defense applications. The same wall reappears in fusion structural materials: the UKAEA review states atomistic capability stops at &quot;single elements or simple binary systems, such as Fe-Cr&quot; while reduced-activation steels demand seven-plus elements plus transmutants — composition space is the shared upstream blocker of at least two national programs.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"203\">[203]</sup></p>\n<p>So here is my position, stated as a bet: composition-space generalization is the single unsolved MLIP problem I am wagering this venture on. MS25-HEA isolates it with zero label noise; the failure is demonstrably coverage and architecture rather than quantum chemistry, so a small lab can attack it — I need the right 10<span class=\"math\">$^4$</span> structures, not a foundation-model budget; and all three candidate levers point at the problem with none yet validated on an HEA benchmark. My product thesis is deliberately narrow: validated per-composition-family potentials — a Ni-superalloy-family potential shipped with error bars on density, lattice constants, γ/γ′ energetics, and SFE distributions — explicitly not universal-potential claims. The fine-tuned 3.5 meV/atom datum says per-family threshold accuracy is within reach of demonstration; the 617.9 meV/atom zero-shot datum says anyone selling universality in composition space today is selling a number the suite already falsified.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup> My go/no-go observable: an element-wise-MoE or Δ-learned model posting ≤2.5 meV/atom on a DFT-labeled, SRO-resolved, multi-composition benchmark. That artifact — not a leaderboard rank — is the unlock the turbines are waiting for.</p>\n" },
]
